:: 80sCrisis [era-silence] {"position":"1000,275","size":"100,100"}
''1980/1985: A march that falls silent''

You feel the atmosphere change, you are stepping onto a very dark part of LGBTQIA+ history, entering the 80s.
A single panel, lit from below, names two young men murdered in Giarre in 1980: a crime that led directly to the founding of ARCIgay in Palermo that same year, the biggest national LGBTQIA+ association.
A little further, the path is lined with photographs of the first AIDS information campaigns from 1985, at a time when fear and stigma surrounded the epidemic - and the movement had to fight for survival before it could fight for rights.

A small caption at the bottom of the panel reads: ''This part of the exhibition is heavier than the others. You may take your time.''

[[Stay here a moment before continuing->AIDSPause]]
[[Keep walking without stopping->CassariniMonument]]


:: AIDSPause [era-silence] {"position":"1000,150","size":"100,100"}
(set: $slowedDown to true)

You stop. The silence around you is part of the exhibit.

A small light illuminates a handwritten membership card for "Il Cassero": Bologna's first lesbian cultural circle, born in these very years, where Pride days began to be celebrated for the first time inside its own walls. 
''The spirit of the fight for rights was returning, despite everything.
''
[[Keep walking->CassariniMonument]]


:: AntiPride [era-peak] {"position":"1775,150","size":"100,100"}
You look at the digital totem and scroll thorugh the newspapers talking about at the time, with a focus on all the crisis caused by the two events (World Pride and the Catholic Jubilee) happening in the same place at the same time.

<a href="https://centrodocumentazionecassero.it/sfoglia?id=42717&mode=2">Read one of the articles here:</a>

[[Keep walking->Pride2000s]]


:: CassariniMonument [era-monument] {"position":"1200,275","size":"100,100"}
''1990: A monument along the way''

A photograph on the wall shows a stone marker in the gardens of Villa Cassarini, Bologna: the monument placed there in 1990, dedicated to the queer victims of Nazi-Fascism.
A pink triangle is carved into the stone. A short text explains: //this symbol once marked homosexual prisoners in concentration camps. The movement reclaimed it, turning a mark of persecution into a sign of identity.//

But the monument means something more. It was placed in a public garden, by the city of Bologna itself — one of the first times an Italian institution officially recognised these victims, and this community, as part of its own history. 
''After the silence of the previous decade, being seen is starting to mean being acknowledged.
''
(if: $slowedDown is true)[
The names of Giarre are still with you as you read. This stone answers them, in its own way: a promise that some things will not be forgotten again.
]

[[Look closer at the monument->CassariniStatue]]

[[Keep walking->Pride94]]


:: CassariniStatue [era-monument] {"position":"1200,150","size":"100,100"}
You run a hand over the carved triangle. The text beside it explains how, decade after decade, LGBTQIA+ movements across Europe turned this symbol of persecution into one of pride and memory.

(set: $textsRead to $textsRead + 1)
You look closely at the carved triangle. The text beside the photograph explains how, decade after decade, LGBTQIA+ movements across Europe turned this symbol of persecution into one of pride and memory.

<figure style="margin:1em 0;">
  <img src="https://cassero.archivio.com/promemoria/api/get-image-thumbnail?id=26966-22c7bea7&version=large" 
