[[Keep walking->Pride94]]


:: CirinnàLaw [era-today] {"position":"1625,525","size":"100,100"}
(set: $textsRead to $textsRead + 1)

You step up to the totem.

On the screen, the text of ''Law no. 76 of 20 May 2016'' — known as the ''Cirinnà law'', after senator Monica Cirinnà who championed it. Approved after years of debate and failed attempts, it is the first legal recognition of same-sex couples in the history of the Italian Republic: reciprocal assistance obligations, inheritance rights, access to a partner's pension.

It is also a compromise: stepchild adoption was removed from the text to secure the votes, and marriage remains out of reach. A historic victory — and an unfinished one.

<a href="https://www.normattiva.it/uri-res/N2Ls?urn:nir:stato:legge:2016-05-20;76" target="_blank">📜 Read the full text of the law on Normattiva, the official portal of Italian legislation (in Italian)</a>

[[Stop and listen at Flavia Madaschi's speech->MadaschiListen]]

[[Keep walking toward the end of the route->RivoltaPride]]


:: Contribute [era-archive] {"position":"650,875","size":"100,100"}
(if: $visitorMessage is "")[
(set: $contributed to false)
You look at the blank card for a moment, then hand it back with a smile. Some things stay unwritten — and that is fine too.
](else:)[
(set: $contributed to true)
You pin your card to the wall, among all the others.

''"Every memory you leave here becomes part of how this march will be told tomorrow."''
]

[[Continue->Ending]]


:: CrossOver [era-archive] {"position":"1175,650","size":"100,100"}
The path ends at a wide doorway. You step through — and the route opens into the Cassero ballroom.

The room feels different from the corridor you have walked so far: a large screen on the far wall showing other pictures from the past, chairs and small tables, headsets waiting on their stands, and a table with papers and pens. 
Everything you have just seen — the posters, the photographs, the words — comes from the collections of the "Flavia Madaschi" Documentation Centre, preserved one floor above you since 1983.

(if: $voicesHeard >= 3)[
A volunteer notices how much time you took with the panels along the way, and smiles: "You really walked with us today."
]

This room holds the last two moments of your visit.

[[Step toward the headsets->VRTransition]]


:: Ending [era-archive] {"position":"475,650","size":"100,100"}
''You are back outside.''

The street looks the same as it did before you entered. But something in how you see it has shifted.

(if: $contributed is true and $voicesHeard >= 3)[\
You leave having truly walked the whole march — stopping at the testimonies, taking your time when it mattered, and leaving a trace of your own among all the others who walked before you.\
]\
(else-if: $contributed is true and $voicesHeard < 3)[\
You leave having added something of your own to this story, even if you walked past more testimonies than you stopped for.\
]\
(else-if: $contributed is false and $voicesHeard >= 3)[\
You leave carrying the testimonies you stopped for, even if you did not add your own to the wall: not yet.\
]\
(else:)[\
You leave having walked the route at your own distance, seeing more than stopping: a first contact with a march you may want to join again.\
]

''Your march, in numbers:''
''Voices you stopped to listen to: '' $voicesHeard
''Texts and documents you examined: '' $textsRead
''Slowed down during the silent stretch: '' $slowedDown
''Left a message on the wall: '' $contributed

(if: $contributed is true)[\
''Your message, now part of the march:''
//"$visitorMessage"//\
]

//''Pride was never only a parade you watch go by. It was, and is, decades of people choosing, again and again, to be seen.''//

<a href="https://fightingforpride.figma.site/" target="_blank">🔍 Keep exploring: all the materials of this exhibition are on the Fighting for Pride web app</a>

''THE END.''


:: EuroPride2011 [era-peak] {"position":"1800,650","size":"100,100"}
Further on, the path becomes its loudest yet: ''Roma, 2011: Europride. About one million people. Lady Gaga speaks to the crowd.''

[[Listen to Gaga's speech to the crowd of EuroPride->EuroPrideListen]]

[[Keep walking->UnioniCivili]]


:: EuroPrideListen [era-peak] {"position":"1800,525","size":"100,100"}
(set: $voicesHeard to $voicesHeard + 1)

You stop under the largest screen of the route. Rome, 11 June 2011: Lady Gaga speaks to a crowd of one million people gathered for the Europride.

<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Gu5k550cGfA" target="_blank">▶ Watch Lady Gaga's Europride speech on YouTube</a>

[[Keep walking->UnioniCivili]]


:: Fuori! {"position":"575,275","size":"100,100"}
A sign nailed to the wall reads: ''FUORI! 1971. The first homosexual liberation group in Italy.''

Further on, a panel shows the history of the Sanremo protest of 5 April 1972, when members of FUORI! interrupted a medical congress that treated homosexuality as an illness. That is the first sign of public rebellion of the Italian LGBTQIA+ community.

Protesters were showing signs with quotes like:
''"Psychiatrists, we came to cure you." "Normality does not exist." "Gay is Proud."''

[[Stop and look at the articles->FuoriRead]]
[[Look at the pictures->FuoriPhoto]]

[[Keep walking->Pisa79]]


:: FuoriPhoto [era-1970s] {"position":"500,150","size":"100,100"}
The pictures show the Sanremo protest of April 1972: a small group of people holding hand-lettered signs, surrounded by police officers and puzzled onlookers. Some of the activists had registered for the congress disguised as doctors before being escorted out.

<a href="https://fightingforpride.figma.site/" target="_blank">🔍 Browse the full FUORI! photo collection on the exhibition web app with this link, or by scanning the QR code you will will find on all totems.</a>
[[Read the article about Sanremo72->FuoriRead]] 
[[Keep walking->Pisa79]]


:: FuoriRead [era-1970s] {"position":"650,150","size":"100,100"}
(set: $textsRead to $textsRead + 1) 
