:: MadaschiListen [era-today] {"position":"1500,525","size":"100,100"}
(set: $voicesHeard to $voicesHeard + 1)

Her recorded voice, from a speech at the Bologna Pride of 2012, fills the last stretch of the path:

''"I am more and more convinced that if we parents also took to the streets for our children's rights, the results would be different."''

(if: $slowedDown is true)[
You think back to the silence of 1980/1985, and her words land even closer.
]

<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PNeYqqplby0" target="_blank">▶ Watch Flavia Madaschi's speech at Bologna Pride 2014</a>

You stand with her words for a moment before the path leads you onward.

[[Keep walking toward the end of the route->RivoltaPride]]


:: MessageMomentNoVR {"position":"650,750","size":"100,100"}
The ballroom is still around you.

Near the exit, a wall is covered with hand-written notes: memories, names, thank-yous, promises — left by everyone who walked this march before you.

A volunteer offers you a card and a pen.

(input-box: 2bind $visitorMessage, "=XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX=", 4)

[[Pin your message to the wall->Contribute]]

[[Simply thank the volunteer and continue->NoContribute]]


:: MessageMomentVR [era-archive] {"position":"775,750","size":"100,100"}
You take off the headset. The ballroom is still around you.

Near the exit, a wall is covered with hand-written notes: memories, names, thank-yous, promises — left by everyone who walked this march before you.

A volunteer offers you a card and a pen.

(input-box: 2bind $visitorMessage, "=XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX=", 4)

[[Pin your message to the wall->Contribute]]

[[Simply thank the volunteer and continue->NoContribute]]


:: NoContribute [era-archive] {"position":"775,875","size":"100,100"}
(set: $contributed to false)
(set: $visitorMessage to "")

You thank the volunteer and take one last look at the wall of notes before moving toward the exit.

[[Continue->Ending]]


:: Pisa79 [era-1970s] {"position":"800,275","size":"100,100"}
''1976/1979 - The march grows''

The path leads you on. You first yourself in front of a new historical step, in particular the first one for the city of Bologna: ''Collettivo Frocialista - Bologna, 1976.'' - born inside the student movements of those years, in this very city.

The walls around you are covered with flyers for the first national gay conventions, come more structured, some more clandestine.

Then, on the wall ahead, you read this caption:'' "Pisa79: the first protest in Italy authorised by the police and a municipality. Considered Italy's first real Pride."''
[[Look closer at the photographs->Pisa79Photo]]

[[Keep walking->80sCrisis]]


:: Pisa79Photo [era-1970s] {"position":"800,150","size":"100,100"}
You crouch to look at the photograph at floor level. Faces, hand-lettered signs, ordinary clothes. A short text explains the march was a response to the murder of a gay man in Livorno and to the violence the community faced everywhere.

Almost five hundred people walked that day. And after almost 50 years, //''you are walking with them today.''//

[[Keep walking->80sCrisis]]


:: Pride2000s [era-peak] {"position":"1950,475","size":"100,100"}
''2007/2013: Visibility and resistance''

The panels here alternate between conflict and celebration.

A caption reads: ''Roma, 2007: Pride held one week after the Family Day, an anti-LGBT demonstration. Around five hundred thousand people march''

Beside it, a row of portraits lines the wall: ''Bologna, 2008.'' Each portrait carries a name, an age, a single plain sentence about love, identity, or violence — part of the real communication campaign from that year's national Pride, held in this very city.

[[Observe the Posters->Pride2000sPhoto]]
[[Keep walking->EuroPride2011]]


:: Pride2000sPhoto [era-peak] {"position":"1950,350","size":"100,100"}
The posters cover the years 2007 and 2008: the Rome Pride held one week after the Family Day, and the Bologna 2008 national campaign, with its portraits of real people — a name, an age, a single plain sentence about love, identity, or violence.

<a href="https://fightingforpride.figma.site/" target="_blank">🔍 Browse the poster collection of the 2000s Prides on the exhibition web app with this link or thorugh the QR on the totems.</a>

[[Keep walking->EuroPride2011]]


:: Pride94 [era-1990s] {"position":"1425,275","size":"100,100"}
''1994/1995: The march finds its name''

The atmosphere changes back again. After the documents of the darkest days, the panels are full of banners, crowds and sunlight. A banner above your head marks the turning point: ''Roma, 1994: the first event to officially carry the name Pride in Italy. About ten thousand people.''
A smaller panel displays excerpts from an interview with Vladimir Luxuria, one of the people who brought the Pride to Italy — on the fear of organising that very first march.

And beside it: ''Bologna, 1995: the national Pride moves here. About fifteen thousand march. Seventy thousand signatures collected this year for civil unions.''

[[Stop and listen to the voice of Vladimir Luxuria->Pride94Listen]]
[[Look at the pictures->Pride9495Photo]]

[[Keep walking->WorldPride]]


:: Pride9495Photo [era-1990s] {"position":"1500,150","size":"100,100"}
The photographs show Rome, June 1994: about ten thousand people behind a single banner, the first march in Italy to officially carry the name "Pride". Next to them, Bologna 1995: the crowd fills the city centre, and volunteers collect signatures for civil unions at the edges of the march — seventy thousand by the end of that year.

<a href="https://fightingforpride.figma.site/" target="_blank">🔍 See the full 1994–1995 photo collection on the exhibition web app with this link or thorugh the QR on the totems.</a>
[[Listen to their words->Pride94Listen]] 
[[Keep walking->WorldPride]]


:: Pride94Listen [era-1990s] {"position":"1375,150","size":"100,100"}
(set: $voicesHeard to $voicesHeard + 1)

You stop among the crowd of silhouettes. From the speaker, the voice of Vladimir Luxuria — activist and artistic director of the Circolo Mario Mieli in those years — recalls the organisation of the very first Pride:

''"But why do almost all the other Western capitals do it, and not here in Rome?"''

''"We thought maybe two hundred people would come. We were wrong, and it was the best mistake of our lives."''

<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20140407085237/http://www.radiopopolareroma.it/taxonomy/term/741">🎧 Listen to the full 2009 Radio Popolare interview.</a>

(if: $voicesHeard >= 2)[
This is not the first voice from the past you have stopped for today.
]
[[Look at the pictures->Pride9495Photo]] 
[[Keep walking->WorldPride]]


:: RivoltaPride [era-today] {"position":"1375,650","size":"100,100"}
''2021: From Pride to Rivolta Pride''

The last banners of the route look different from all the others: rougher, hand-made, louder. And they do not speak only of LGBTQIA+ rights.

Starting in 2021, marches across Italy take a new name: ''Rivolta Pride'' — Pride Revolt. The community that spent fifty years fighting to be recognised now takes to the streets alongside its allies for a wider set of battles: workers' rights, migrants' rights, the fight against racism, against violence on women, for those who have the least voice of all.

It is the same lesson this march has carried from its very first steps, turned outward: no one should have to fight for their rights alone.

[[Keep walking toward the end of the route->CrossOver]]


:: Start [era-start] {"position":"250,275","size":"100,100"}
You step into the Cassero courtyard. You see two long walls building somewhat of a narrow path.

There are no rooms to visit. There is only one road, and it is a march. Step onto it, and you will be walking through fifty years of Pride in Italy. 
''Are you ready?
''
[[You step onto the path->Stonewall]]

(set: $textsRead to 0)
(set: $slowedDown to false)
(set: $contributed to false)
(set: $voicesHeard to 0)
(set: $visitorMessage to "")


:: Stonewall [era-1970s] {"position":"375,275","size":"100,100"}
''1969 - The global background''

The path opens with some pictures of protests, you see also some newspaper articles hanged around, all referencing to "The Stonewall Riots".
We are in the United States.

You are maybe wondering; //why start elsewhere when the exhibition is about Italy?//
[[Read the panel to find out the reason->StonewallInfo]]
[[Keep walking->Fuori!]]


:: StonewallInfo [era-1970s] {"position":"375,150","size":"100,100"}
The Stonewall Riots were a series of protests that began on June 28, 1969, after a police raid on the StoneWall Inn, a popular gay bar in New York city. Instead of dispersing, members of the LGBTQ+ community resisted police harassment, leading to several days of demonstrations.

It is considered a ''turning point in global queer history''. 
It sparked the modern LGBTQIA+ rights movement, inspired the //creation of activist organizations and led to the first Pride marches. //

[[You understand and look further on->Fuori!]]


:: UnioniCivili [era-today] {"position":"1575,650","size":"100,100"}
''2016/2021: The march today''

The panels in this last stretch feel closer to the present - the photographs are in colour, the faces could be people you know.
A caption reads: ''2016: civil unions are approved by the Italian Parliament.''
Beside it stands an interactive totem. On its screen, the full newspaper article on the approval of the Cirinnà law — the vote, the years of debate that preceded it, what the law finally recognised and what it left out. You can read it in Italian or in English, at your own pace.
[[Stop and read it->CirinnàLaw]]

Beside it: ''2021: Pride marches across Italy shift focus again, carried forward by new generations and new battles.''

At the very end of this section, one display stands apart: a single photograph of a woman in a white T-shirt. Flavia Madaschi, mother of a gay son, who marched at every Pride wearing the words "Straight or gay, you are all my children." The Documentation Centre that preserves everything you have seen today carries her name.

[[Stop and listen to her voice->MadaschiListen]]

[[Keep walking toward the end of the route->RivoltaPride]]


:: VRTransition [era-archive] {"position":"975,650","size":"100,100"}
Now look in front of you and walk towards the VR headsets.

You are eager to see what those are there for. 

You put on one headset, and you start experiencing the Pride march.

---

''(If an headset is not available, you can watch the same experience here — a 360° recording of the Rome Pride, 2016.)''
<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_YSQOnbODAQ" target="_blank">▶ Watch the 360° Pride experience on YouTube</a>

[[I have experienced the VR. Continue->MessageMomentVR]]
[[I prefer to watch it on my phone->MessageMomentNoVR]]


:: WorldPride [era-peak] {"position":"1725,275","size":"100,100"}
''2000: The march becomes a sea of people''

A wall of photographs shows Rome in the year 2000: between three hundred thousand and half a million people at the World Pride, with international guests like Gloria Gaynor, the Village People, and RuPaul.

A second, darker panel sits just beside the celebration: a short text on the campaign waged against the march before it happened: rumours, leaked private material, an attempt by parts of the Vatican and the political establishment to stop it from ever taking place.

//''The two panels, side by side, tell the whole story: the march that almost did not happen became one of the largest LGBTQIA+ gatherings ever held in Italy.''//
[[Look closer at the wall of photographs->WorldPridePhotos]]
[[Read the articles about the campaign against Pride->AntiPride]]
[[Keep walking->Pride2000s]]


:: WorldPridePhotos [era-peak] {"position":"1650,150","size":"100,100"}
You step closer. Rainbow flags fill every frame, far further than the eye can follow. A small caption notes: ''"This is the moment the Italian Pride stopped being a small, fragile event and became impossible to ignore."''

[[Keep walking->Pride2000s]]


:: storyHeader [header] {"position":"100,150","size":"100,100"}



:: StoryScript [script]
(function () {
  function buildCrowds(root) {
    (root || document).querySelectorAll('.crowd-figures:not([data-built])').forEach(function (el) {
      var count = parseInt(el.getAttribute('data-count'), 10) || 0;
      for (var i = 0; i < count; i++) {
        var span = document.createElement('span');
        span.className = 'crowd-figure';
        el.appendChild(span);
      }
      el.setAttribute('data-built', '1');
    });
  }

  function init() {
    var story = document.querySelector('tw-story');
    if (!story) { setTimeout(init, 100); return; }
    buildCrowds(story);
    var observer = new MutationObserver(function () {
      buildCrowds(story);
    });
    observer.observe(story, { childList: true, subtree: true });
  }

  init();
})();

:: StoryStylesheet [stylesheet]
/* ============================================================
   PRIDE — THE MARCH THROUGH TIME
   Stylesheet for Twine (Harlowe)  —  v3 (fixed: flag now persists across passages)
   ------------------------------------------------------------
   WHAT CHANGED IN v3:
   - The flag bar is now pure CSS on <tw-story>::after, which
     never gets destroyed between passages (unlike <tw-passage>,
     which Harlowe recreates every time you click a link). This
     is what makes it actually stay visible on every page.
   - The crowd silhouette script now uses a MutationObserver,
     so it re-runs automatically every time Harlowe swaps in a
     new passage, instead of running once and never again.
   ------------------------------------------------------------
   SETUP — read this first:

   1. This stylesheet goes in Story > Edit Story Stylesheet.

   2. Your .tw file must contain a passage named storyHeader,
      tagged [header] (the tag is literally the word "header",
      lowercase, added via the passage's "+Tag" button). It
      only needs to contain the <script> block for the crowd
      silhouettes now — the flag bar no longer needs any HTML,
      it is drawn entirely by this stylesheet.

   3. Tag EVERY passage with ONE era tag:

      Start                                  -> era-start
      Stretch1, Stretch1Listen,
      Stretch2, Stretch2Photo                -> era-1970s
      Stretch3, Stretch3Pause,
      Stretch3Continue                       -> era-silence
      Stretch4, Stretch4Triangle             -> era-monument
      Stretch5, Stretch5Listen               -> era-1990s
      Stretch6, Stretch6Photos,
      Stretch7, Stretch7Portraits            -> era-peak
      Stretch8, Stretch8Madaschi             -> era-today
      CrossOver, Contribute,
      NoContribute, Ending                   -> era-archive

      (use the same tag spelling exactly, all lowercase)
   ============================================================ */


/* ============================================================
   BASE RESET
   ============================================================ */

tw-story {
  font-family: 'Georgia', 'Times New Roman', serif;
  background-color: #f4f1ea;
  color: #1a1a1a;
  transition: background-color 1.2s ease, color 0.8s ease;
  padding-bottom: 56px; /* room for the fixed flag bar */
  padding-left: 5%;
  padding-right: 5%;
}

tw-passage {
  max-width: 1100px;
  margin: 0 auto;
  padding: 2.5em 3em;
  line-height: 1.75;
  font-size: 1.08em;
  position: relative;
  animation: passage-fade-in 0.9s ease;
}

@keyframes passage-fade-in {
  from { opacity: 0; transform: translateY(8px); }
  to   { opacity: 1; transform: translateY(0); }
}

/* ---------- LINKS: unvisited vs visited ---------- */

tw-passage a.link,
tw-link {
  text-decoration: none;
  border-bottom: 2px solid currentColor;
  padding-bottom: 1px;
  font-weight: bold;
  transition: opacity 0.2s ease, border-bottom-style 0.2s ease;
}

tw-passage a.link:hover,
tw-link:hover {
  opacity: 0.65;
}

tw-passage a.link:visited,
tw-passage a.link.visited {
  border-bottom-style: dashed;
  opacity: 0.55;
}

/* ---------- MESSAGE INPUT BOX ---------- */

tw-passage textarea {
  background: rgba(255, 252, 240, 0.6);
  border: 1px solid #b8a06c;
  border-radius: 6px;
  color: #2b2014;
  font-family: 'Georgia', serif;
  font-size: 1em;
  padding: 0.6em;
}

tw-passage textarea:focus {
  outline: none;
  border-color: #7a5a23;
}

/* ============================================================
   FIXED PROGRESS FLAG  (bottom bar)
   ------------------------------------------------------------
   Pure CSS, built with linear-gradient stripes on a pseudo
   element of <tw-story> itself (not of the passage), because
   <tw-story> is never destroyed between passages while
   <tw-passage> is recreated on every navigation. This is what
   makes the bar persist across the whole playthrough instead
   of only showing on the first passage.

   Its saturation/brightness is controlled per-era further
   down via a filter applied to tw-story::after.
   ============================================================ */

tw-story {
  position: relative;
}

tw-story::after {
  content: "";
  position: fixed;
  bottom: 0;
  left: 0;
  width: 100%;
  height: 14px;
  z-index: 999;
  pointer-events: none;
  background: linear-gradient(
    90deg,
    #e4572e 0%, #e4572e 16.6%,
    #f3a712 16.6%, #f3a712 33.2%,
    #f6e042 33.2%, #f6e042 49.8%,
    #2e933c 49.8%, #2e933c 66.4%,
    #1b6ca8 66.4%, #1b6ca8 83%,
    #6a4c93 83%, #6a4c93 100%
  );
  filter: grayscale(0.85) brightness(0.9);
  transition: filter 1.4s ease;
}


/* ============================================================
   CROWD FIGURES
   ------------------------------------------------------------
   .crowd-figures is an empty <div data-count="N"> in the
   passage text. The header passage's script (see the .tw
   file) builds N <span class="crowd-figure"> children inside
   it each time a passage renders.
   ============================================================ */

.crowd-figures {
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
  gap: 4px;
  align-items: flex-end;
  margin: 1em 0;
  min-height: 28px;
}

.crowd-figure {
  width: 14px;
  height: 26px;
  flex-shrink: 0;
  background-repeat: no-repeat;
  background-size: contain;
  background-position: bottom;
  opacity: 0.85;
  background-image: url("data:image/svg+xml;utf8,<svg xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg' viewBox='0 0 24 48'><circle cx='12' cy='8' r='7' fill='%23000'/><path d='M2 48 L4 22 Q12 14 20 22 L22 48 Z' fill='%23000'/></svg>");
}

.crowd-overflow .crowd-figure:last-child {
  opacity: 1;
  width: 18px;
}

.crowd-overflow::after {
  content: "+ as many more as the eye can hold";
  display: block;
  font-size: 0.8em;
  font-style: italic;
  opacity: 0.7;
  margin-top: 4px;
  flex-basis: 100%;
}


/* ============================================================
   ERA: START
   ============================================================ */
tw-story:has(tw-passage[tags~="era-start"]) {
  background-color: #f4f1ea;
  color: #1a1a1a;
}
tw-story:has(tw-passage[tags~="era-start"])::after {
  filter: grayscale(1) brightness(0.85);
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-start"] {
  font-family: 'Courier New', monospace;
  letter-spacing: 0.3px;
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-start"] .crowd-figure {
  filter: grayscale(1);
}


/* ============================================================
   ERA: 1970s — FUORI!, Sanremo, Pisa79
   ============================================================ */
tw-story:has(tw-passage[tags~="era-1970s"]) {
  background-color: #ece8df;
  color: #181818;
}
tw-story:has(tw-passage[tags~="era-1970s"])::after {
  filter: grayscale(0.95) brightness(0.85);
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-1970s"] {
  font-family: 'Courier New', monospace;
  border-left: 4px solid #b3262c;
  padding-left: 2em;
  background-image:
    repeating-linear-gradient(0deg, rgba(0,0,0,0.025) 0px, rgba(0,0,0,0.025) 1px, transparent 1px, transparent 3px);
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-1970s"] em,
tw-passage[tags~="era-1970s"] i {
  color: #b3262c;
  font-style: normal;
  font-weight: bold;
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-1970s"] a.link {
  color: #b3262c;
  border-bottom-color: #b3262c;
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-1970s"] .crowd-figure {
  filter: grayscale(1) contrast(1.2);
}


/* ============================================================
   ERA: SILENCE — 1980/85, Giarre, AIDS, mourning
   ============================================================ */
tw-story:has(tw-passage[tags~="era-silence"]) {
  background-color: #1c1c1e;
  color: #c9c7c4;
}
tw-story:has(tw-passage[tags~="era-silence"])::after {
  filter: grayscale(1) brightness(0.4);
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-silence"] {
  font-family: 'Georgia', serif;
  font-weight: 300;
  letter-spacing: 0.4px;
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-silence"] em,
tw-passage[tags~="era-silence"] i {
  color: #e7a0b2;
  font-style: italic;
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-silence"] a.link {
  color: #e7a0b2;
  border-bottom-color: #6b4a52;
}


/* ============================================================
   ERA: MONUMENT — 1990, Villa Cassarini, the pink triangle
   ============================================================ */
tw-story:has(tw-passage[tags~="era-monument"]) {
  background-color: #2e3530;
  color: #d8ddd4;
}
tw-story:has(tw-passage[tags~="era-monument"])::after {
  filter: grayscale(0.9) brightness(0.55);
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-monument"] {
  font-family: 'Georgia', serif;
  background-image:
    radial-gradient(circle at 20% 30%, rgba(255,255,255,0.03) 0px, transparent 40px),
    radial-gradient(circle at 70% 80%, rgba(255,255,255,0.03) 0px, transparent 60px),
    radial-gradient(circle at 50% 50%, rgba(0,0,0,0.04) 0px, transparent 90px);
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-monument"] em,
tw-passage[tags~="era-monument"] i {
  color: #e7a0b2;
  font-style: italic;
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-monument"] a.link {
  color: #9fb89a;
  border-bottom-color: #9fb89a;
}


/* ============================================================
   ERA: 1990s — 1994/95, the march finds its name
   ============================================================ */
tw-story:has(tw-passage[tags~="era-1990s"]) {
  background-color: #fdf7ec;
  color: #2a2a2a;
}
tw-story:has(tw-passage[tags~="era-1990s"])::after {
  filter: grayscale(0.4) brightness(0.95);
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-1990s"] {
  font-family: 'Georgia', serif;
  border-top: 6px solid;
  border-image: linear-gradient(90deg, #e4572e, #f3a712, #2e933c, #1b6ca8, #6a4c93) 1;
  padding-top: 1.5em;
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-1990s"] em,
tw-passage[tags~="era-1990s"] i {
  color: #1b6ca8;
  font-style: italic;
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-1990s"] a.link {
  color: #c1440e;
  border-bottom-color: #c1440e;
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-1990s"] .crowd-figure {
  filter: sepia(0.4);
}


/* ============================================================
   ERA: PEAK — 2000 / 2007-2013, World Pride, Europride
   ============================================================ */
tw-story:has(tw-passage[tags~="era-peak"]) {
  background-color: #fffdf5;
  color: #1a1a1a;
}
tw-story:has(tw-passage[tags~="era-peak"])::after {
  filter: none;
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-peak"] {
  font-family: 'Verdana', 'Arial', sans-serif;
  border: none;
  border-radius: 10px;
  background-image:
    linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(228, 87, 46, 0.07), rgba(243, 167, 18, 0.07), rgba(46, 147, 60, 0.07), rgba(27, 108, 168, 0.07), rgba(106, 76, 147, 0.07));
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-peak"] em,
tw-passage[tags~="era-peak"] i {
  color: #c1440e;
  font-style: normal;
  font-weight: bold;
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-peak"] a.link {
  color: #6a4c93;
  border-bottom-color: #6a4c93;
  font-weight: bold;
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-peak"] .crowd-figure {
  background-image: url("data:image/svg+xml;utf8,<svg xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg' viewBox='0 0 24 48'><circle cx='12' cy='8' r='7' fill='%236a4c93'/><path d='M2 48 L4 22 Q12 14 20 22 L22 48 Z' fill='%23c1440e'/></svg>");
}


/* ============================================================
   ERA: TODAY — 2016/2021, civil unions, new generations
   ============================================================ */
tw-story:has(tw-passage[tags~="era-today"]) {
  background-color: #f2f0f7;
  color: #2c2a35;
}
tw-story:has(tw-passage[tags~="era-today"])::after {
  filter: grayscale(0.3) brightness(1);
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-today"] {
  font-family: 'Helvetica Neue', 'Arial', sans-serif;
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-today"] em,
tw-passage[tags~="era-today"] i {
  color: #8868b3;
  font-style: italic;
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-today"] a.link {
  color: #5a4a7a;
  border-bottom-color: #b6a6d6;
}


/* ============================================================
   ERA: ARCHIVE — the Documentation Centre
   ============================================================ */
tw-story:has(tw-passage[tags~="era-archive"]) {
  background-color: #e9dfc9;
  color: #2b2014;
}
tw-story:has(tw-passage[tags~="era-archive"])::after {
  filter: grayscale(0.6) brightness(0.8) sepia(0.3);
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-archive"] {
  font-family: 'Georgia', serif;
  border: 1px solid #b8a06c;
  border-radius: 4px;
  padding: 2.5em;
  background-color: rgba(255, 252, 240, 0.4);
  background-image:
    repeating-linear-gradient(90deg, rgba(120,90,40,0.02) 0px, rgba(120,90,40,0.02) 2px, transparent 2px, transparent 6px);
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-archive"] em,
tw-passage[tags~="era-archive"] i {
  color: #7a5a23;
  font-style: italic;
}
tw-passage[tags~="era-archive"] a.link {
  color: #7a5a23;
  border-bottom-color: #b8a06c;
}


/* ============================================================
   FALLBACK for browsers without :has() support
   ============================================================ */
@supports not (selector(:has(*))) {
  tw-story {
    background-color: #f4f1ea;
    color: #1a1a1a;
  }
  tw-story::after {
    filter: none;
  }
}